You’re officially at the **Step 11 Testimony**, the final checkpoint before moving up. This is where you **speak your truth**—summarizing what you’ve learned from each step, how you’ve changed, and how you’re applying it.

Since you can’t read directly from your notes during group, let’s make you a clean verbal version that hits all the requirements but still sounds like *you*.

---

### ✅ **MRT-Approved Step 11 Testimony Template (use this to speak from memory):**

&gt; “My name is [Brooke], and I’m on Step 11.  
&gt; Through this process, I’ve learned a lot—not just about my choices, but about how I saw myself and others.  
&gt; 
&gt; In Step 1, I saw how my past beliefs shaped my behavior. I justified a lot by saying, ‘That’s just how I am,’ instead of changing.  
&gt; 
&gt; In Step 2, I recognized how my thinking was all over the place. I made decisions based on feelings instead of facts.  
&gt; 
&gt; In Step 3, I looked at who I blamed for my problems. And I had to admit—nobody forced me to stay stuck. I did that.  
&gt; 
&gt; In Step 4, I saw the patterns I kept repeating—especially in how I handled family, relationships, and myself.  
&gt; 
&gt; In Step 5, I realized I’d been running from responsibility and calling it ‘independence.’ I wasn’t being free—I was avoiding.  
&gt; 
&gt; Step 6 showed me how much my choices were tied to old excuses. I was acting out of pain and fear, not values.  
&gt; 
&gt; In Step 7, I learned that trust has to be earned—by others, and by me.  
&gt; 
&gt; In Step 8, I learned that forgiveness isn’t forgetting—it’s letting go so I can move forward.  
&gt; 
&gt; In Step 9, I helped others, and it reminded me that I have value beyond what I’ve been through.  
&gt; 
&gt; In Step 10, I had to face how I still let certain thoughts and behaviors drag me down—and I made a decision not to let that happen anymore.  
&gt; 
&gt; And in Step 11, I looked at the best and worst moments of my life. I realized that I was usually the one holding myself back. And now I don’t want to do that anymore.  
&gt; 
&gt; I’m not perfect, but I’m done running from myself. I’m working to stay real and keep moving forward—because I know what it looks like when I don’t.”

